You take a deliberate bite of the scone, locking eyes with Ms. Greene as you chew. The sweetness of apricot and butter barely registers over the tension thickening between you.

Ms. Greene doesn’t blink. She watches, expectant—waiting for an apology, an excuse, something.

Instead, you take another bite.

A flicker of emotion—annoyance? Disbelief? Contempt?—crosses her face before her expression smooths back into its usual, steely disapproval.

Maybe this wasn’t the best decision, but then again, when has Ms. Greene ever approved of you?
